			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Q.  How would a player get to be force sensitive?
<br />

<br />
A.  I think the character should choose when creating their character.  I like the idea of the sensitivity being random, but in a MMORPG, that is to hard to make work.  You would have hundreds of people mass creating characters until they got a character who was sensitive.  I do like the idea of having characters randomly start out at various levels of force awareness.  Maybe lev 1 to 5 on the "force power" scale.  This would be truly random, and only affect maybe the first couple of quests to gain "force power".
<br />

<br />
Q.  How would a player get to be a Jedi?
<br />

<br />
A.  Through training.  Lots of training and devotion.  I think there should be a game time aspect AND a real time aspect.  This would prevent someone from powerleveling a Jedi, yet would not prevent the casual player from becoming a Jedi within a reasonable time.  I think the training should consist of seeking out various masters/artifacts and accepting and completing quests from them to earn Jedi status.
<br />

<br />
Q.  How do you make Jedi feel rare and mysterious?
<br />

<br />
A.  I think the above answer would help keep the Jedi population down, and give them a "mysterious" feel.  Another idea would be to have them randomly report "bogus" information when you con them.  Nothing to drastic, but maybe have there HP reading be higher than normal, or some other attribute report lower than normal.  Kind of give a sense that Jedi are not normal (they aren't) and normal method of con'ning them wouldn't always be 100% accurate.
<br />

<br />
Q.  Would you try to balance the Jedi profession against others? If so, how? 
<br />

<br />
A.  Don't balance them completely.  They should be more powerful characters, but they should never be invincible.  Everyone has a weak point.  Luke, Emperor Palpatine, Vader and others all had a weak side.  This weak side should be exploitable in game.  This does not mean the Jedi can't find teammates/artifacts to cover the weakness, but the weakness should exist.  Jedi's should be balanced in an overall sense so they do not become the "supreme beings" in the game.
<br />

<br />
Q. What incentives to you give to have Jedi players “act appropriately”?
<br />

<br />
A.  First off, you have to decide what is "acting appropriately".  In the paper based RPG, you earn Force Points and Dark Side Points, given at the discretion of the GM.  You can use these points to help your character out in the course of the game.  Maybe something that is a cross between Everquests AA and the Force Points would work?  As a "light Jedi" you earn "good points" that will let you learn higher skills only available to the "light Jedi".  As a "Dark Jedi" you earn "dark points" that will let you learn higher skills only available to the "dark Jedi".  Switching from Dark to Light would let you still keep those other points, but it would cost you more to use the skills that do not follow your alignment.  Using DP when your Light would push you further to the DP side.  And vice versa with the light side.
<br />

<br />
Than Landrigan
<br />
Outlaw and trouble-make for hire.
<br />

<br />
[ October 11, 2002: Message edited by: Than ]</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
