				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">How would a player get to be Force Sensitive? --- IMO, THis should be something gained my mear chance. and very rare at that. My example is- Seromin killes a beast on tatooine and looks beast claw, normally seromin would just sell beast claw to vendor for small change, instead Seromin drops beast claw on the ground game command random inncodent like random dice 1-500 and gets lucky enough to roll the exact number needed which gives Seromin a sensation new to him. game message to Seromin "You  sudden feel dizzy from a faint sensation." This message randomly generated so that no two players recieve the samee message. From this point forward that player now is force sensitive. but this does not mean he knows about it or knows what to do. His next task would have to be a "chance happening" as well before he learns to seak out a jedi master or low skilled jedi npc to point him in the right direction to his training. hence still being random and difficult to maintain. Also the fact that Seromin stumbled accross the right action to come upon his force awareness. That situation was unique to him. So figure For seromin to become force aware. Character creation sets specific events that could occure to trigger, then 1-500 chance he will become force aware. THis way the game size will make Jedi rare. Then those that become aware have a long full game experiance of becomeing a jedi. ---
<br />

<br />
How would a player get to be a Jedi? ---
<br />
Through a series of quests and practice and npc confrontaions. The jedi are percieved as Solitary ppl in alot of the Star wars universe. So BEcomeing a Jedi should be based on one player going from awareness to jedi master though his solitary deeps BUT still useing other players to obtain needed "Quest items" Confrontations would be killing certain NPC or certain ranking PA's of PC's. or even other PC jedi or dark Jedi.---
<br />
How do you make Jedi feel rare and mysterious? --- A) they should be able to conciel their apearance and pose as another profession. They should be able to go unseen. but not invis. more like blending in. b) also the factor of players becomeing Jedi should be long an difficult in some way that it would be the same for casual and hard core gamers. Dedication would be key and following the solitary game life in becomeing one.---
<br />

<br />
Would you try to balance the Jedi profession against others? If so, how?
<br />
--- Jedi are highly skilled and have MUCH advantage, yet they are so dedicated in their Dicipline they do not have "time" to become skillful in much else, so they should be very limited in what other skills they can learn outside the Jedi Dicipline, and limit on how skillful they can become. example. Jedi may only be diplomats, so they are excelled at self difence and diplomacy and negotiation, but they cannot fire a blaster safely or effectivly or even program a druid or pick a lock, were as a non-jedi can master more skills at one time so a non- jedi may pick locks while blasting his aggrssors, while commanding his druid to set a lock behind him and scamble the code, all at the same time.--- 
<br />

<br />
What incentives to you give to have Jedi players “act appropriately”? Jedi are noble stern, seriious, maintained, and Hidden. Thy dont flaunt their powers or show themselves, they act nobly and protect the innocent. They do not use their powers for self gain. Were as dark jedi are the opposit. Your actions should decide whether you are of sith or not. Sith will have advatages an not, as will Jedi. So players that want to play a good noble jedi will follow strict rules or fall into the HATES sith Jedi ranking were he will be hated and mistrusted, yet have other options as well. So it should depend on the players interest. But be very strict guidelines. And there should be the neutral mara jade setting were a player can kind of sit in the middle and stop themselves from falling to the dark side, yet not be good enough to become a Good Jedi, the disadvatage of that would be they can never advance nor master their Discipline. IT should also be esy to fall to the dark side yet extreemly difficult to be brought back to the light. A) for game consistancy. B) to keep players from letting themselves slip to the dark side out of non-careing. Alot to loose or gain either way. And should be ver y distinct.--
<br />

<br />
As always I hope my ideas feed others ideas so that a plausable development of the discussion can be made for the developers of SWG. Thank you.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
