				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Here are a few of my thoughts on these matters.
<br />

<br />
Q. How would a player get to be force sensitive?
<br />
A. Each player has the potential to become force sensitive, however they find that they are blocked and the force is dormant in them, they must, after finding someone able to test them for this, research ways to "unblock" themselves. There should be diffrent ways needed to do this, so that it's not always the same for everyone, so after the first person finds the path, he or she wont have every friend a jedi within the week.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Q. How would a player get to be a Jedi?
<br />

<br />
A. He must first find a jedi master, of the light or dark side, then convince him he is worthy of the training. he must apprentice himself for a long time, and must face many trials on his way. The lure of the dark side must be overcome to be a light jedi, so the quests must have many moral issues that need to be overcome, for both sides. There must be an alignment system for this. The Jedi MUST follow the path he chooses alignment to the letter, any deviation (succuming to the darkside) and he is booted from trainin.
<br />

<br />
Q. How do you make Jedi feel rare and mysterious?
<br />

<br />
A. the abilities one gains and the sence of accomplishment in becoming on is a start, but to maintain this, jedi are given missions, and must check in with thier superiors on thier status, gaining access to the jedi councle. Jedi should feel they are "making a diffrence" to the game, whether it's political or military. A guild system should be implemented for each type of jedi, with strict rules that must be followed.
<br />

<br />
Q. Would you try to balance the Jedi profession against others? If so, how? 
<br />

<br />
A. The ways of the jedi are not for the meek, balance should be in their strict moral code. Jedi should have to go PVP, and activly fight the opposite side. And while they should be supperior, they must follow stricter guidlines, forcing them to question their actions more. Light Jedi cannot randomly attack and kill innocents, for example, and while dark jedi can, they are kept on a tight leash by thier dark masters, and the price of failure to those masters is extreme.
<br />

<br />
Q. What incentives to you give to have Jedi players “act appropriately”?
<br />

<br />
A. As stated above, jedi should be required to follow thier moral code, or lose thier ranking as jedi, Jedi masters can "block" other jedi if they are deemed unworthy of the title. An alignment system would have to be in place.
<br />
Missions would also help, the game should have quests in which only jedi can take part. He must activly do things to help his side. to become a master, one should have to take on, and "graduate" apprentices. To do this would require him to search out and put others on the path of the jedi, testing them for force sensitivity, and aiding them in "unblocking" thier latent powers.
<br />
To become a grandmaster, one would have to have helped others become master jedi, and not have faltered in thier faith.
<br />
Each stage should have quests to make one question his faith and try to lure them to the other side. when or if the jedi does, they lose all rank and powers of the jedi except the very basics, they are still force sensitive. But thier names are put on a list in game and they are given out as missions for the opposing jedi to take on. they must then find a master of their new side and apprentice under him to gain back thier power as a jedi.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
